  <page>

    <exercise>
      <title>Substitution Method</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Evaluate <m>\displaystyle \int 2x \sqrt{1+x^2} \, dx</m> using substitution.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Let <m>u = 1 + x^2</m>, then <m>du = 2x \, dx</m>. Substituting into the integral gives:
          <md>
            <mrow>\int 2x \sqrt{1+x^2} \, dx \amp = \int \sqrt{u} \, du</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp = \frac{2}{3} u^{3/2} + C\amp = \frac{2}{3} (1+x^2)^{3/2} + C</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
<exercise>
  <title>Integration by Substitution</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Evaluate <m>\displaystyle \int x \sin(x^2) \, dx</m>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Let <m>u = x^2</m>. Then <m>du = 2x \, dx</m>, which implies <m>x \, dx = \frac{1}{2} du</m>.
      Substituting these into the integral:
      <md>
        <mrow>\int x \sin(x^2) \, dx \amp = \int \sin(u) \cdot \frac{1}{2} \, du</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2} \int \sin(u) \, du</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = -\frac{1}{2} \cos(u) + C</mrow>
      </md>
      Substituting back <m>u = x^2</m>:
      <me>-\frac{1}{2} \cos(x^2) + C</me>
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
  <title>Area Between Curves</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find the area of the region enclosed by the graphs of <m>y = x^2 - 2</m> and <m>y = x</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <figure xml:id="fig-area-between-curves">
  <caption>Region enclosed by <m>y = x</m> and <m>y = x^2 - 2</m></caption>
  <image width="70%">
    <description>A parabola opening upward and a diagonal line intersecting at (-1,-1) and (2,2), with the region between them shaded.</description>
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}
        \begin{axis}[
          axis lines = middle,
          xlabel = \(x\),
          ylabel = \(y\),
          xmin=-2.5, xmax=3,
          ymin=-3, ymax=4,
          grid=major,
          samples=100
        ]
        <!-- Shade the region between the curves -->
        <!--\addplot [
            fill=gray, 
            fill opacity=0.3, 
            draw=none, 
            domain=-1:2
        ] {x} \closedcycle;
        \addplot [
            fill=white, 
            draw=none, 
            domain=-1:2
        ] {x^2-2} \closedcycle;-->
        
        <!-- Plot the functions -->
        \addplot [domain=-2:2.2, blue, thick] {x^2 - 2};
        \addlegendentry{\(y = x^2 - 2\)}
        \addplot [domain=-1.5:2.5, red, thick] {x};
        \addlegendentry{\(y = x\)}

        <!-- Intersection points -->
        \addplot [only marks, mark=*, black] coordinates {(-1,-1) (2,2)};
        \node [below left] at (axis cs:-1,-1) {\small (-1,-1)};
        \node [above left] at (axis cs:2,2) {\small (2,2)};
        \end{axis}
      \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
  </image>
</figure>

    <p>
      First, find the points of intersection by setting the equations equal to each other:
      <me>x^2 - 2 = x \implies x^2 - x - 2 = 0 \implies (x - 2)(x + 1) = 0</me>
      The curves intersect at <m>x = -1</m> and <m>x = 2</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      On the interval <m>[-1, 2]</m>, the line <m>y = x</m> is above the parabola <m>y = x^2 - 2</m>. The area <m>A</m> is given by:
      <md>
        <mrow>A \amp = \int_{-1}^{2} [x - (x^2 - 2)] \, dx = \int_{-1}^{2} (-x^2 + x + 2) \, dx</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \left[ -\frac{x^3}{3} + \frac{x^2}{2} + 2x \right]_{-1}^{2}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \left( -\frac{8}{3} + \frac{4}{2} + 4 \right) - \left( \frac{1}{3} + \frac{1}{2} - 2 \right)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \left( -\frac{8}{3} + 6 \right) - \left( \frac{1}{3} - \frac{3}{2} \right)</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp = \frac{10}{3} - \left( -\frac{7}{6} \right) = \frac{20}{6} + \frac{7}{6} = \frac{27}{6} = 4.5</mrow>
      </md>
      The area of the region is <m>4.5</m> square units.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>


</page>
</worksheet>